Soft-tissue neck/back injury but supported by ER visit, imaging, PT and wage loss. Need full medical records, wage docs and prior-claim check. Assuming clean priors and adequate BI limits, case supports funding up to about 12k.}

{Case #=2, Case Type=Medical Malpractice, Court Index Number=12L03-2311-MD-004589, Date of Incident=11/02/2023, Lead Source=Digital Ad, Plaintiff Name=Jared Michael Fulton, Recommended Max Funding=25000, Requested Amount=50000, Risk Level=Moderate-High, State=Illinois, Summary=Failure to diagnose appendicitis at first ER visit; rupture 48 hours later, emergency surgery and several inpatient days., Underwriting Notes=Classic failure-to-diagnose pattern with clear progression from missed appendicitis to rupture and hospitalization. Need confirmation suit is filed, expert supporting breach and causation, and med-bill summary. Med-mal is slow and expert-heavy, so staged funding in the 20–25k range is prudent once expert support and coverage are confirmed.}

{Case #=3, Case Type=Slip and Fall, Court Index Number=18CV-2401-PR-000973, Date of Incident=01/09/2024, Lead Source=Direct Plaintiff Call, Plaintiff Name=Marcus Evan Ridley, Recommended Max Funding=7500, Requested Amount=15000, Risk Level=Moderate, State=Ohio, Summary=Grocery store slip from refrigeration leak; no warning signs; fractured wrist, brace and OT; limits lifting and household tasks., Underwriting Notes=Premises claim with potentially strong notice if video shows a long-standing puddle and prior cooler issues. Objective fracture and OT support damages but upside is capped. Need incident report, maintenance logs, video and full med/wage docs. Assuming negligence and coverage, 6–7.5k funding is reasonable.}

{Case #=4, Case Type=Workplace Injury, Court Index Number=03WC-2306-IN-002764, Date of Incident=06/21/2023, Lead Source=Union Referral, Plaintiff Name=Noah James Corbett, Recommended Max Funding=12000, Requested Amount=30000, Risk Level=Moderate, State=Michigan, Summary=Warehouse forklift struck from behind by coworker; low-back strain with radiating pain; conservative care and restricted duty., Underwriting Notes=Good mechanism but exposure may be mostly workers comp unless there is a viable third-party defendant. Need clarity on comp benefits, separate negligence claim, contracts and lien amounts. If comp-only, funding should be modest; with a strong third-party case and coverage, 10–12k is reasonable.}

{Case #=5, Case Type=Products Liability, Court Index Number=49D10-2309-PL-000811, Date of Incident=09/05/2023, Lead Source=Co-Counsel Referral, Plaintiff Name=Brandon Tyler Vance, Recommended Max Funding=18000, Requested Amount=40000, Risk Level=Moderate, State=Indiana, Summary=New power drill allegedly short-circuited and partially exploded in normal use; burns and deep lacerations to dominant hand; missed work as mechanic., Underwriting Notes=Product defect case with significant dominant-hand injury.
